     4→/** AST class definitions.  These definitions anticipate the definition and implementation of an interpreter based
     5→  * on static distance coordinates (with different variable, map, let nodes) which will be done in Project 7.  Note that 
     6→  * SDAST and AST have many node types in common. The AST type from earlier Projects is now called SymAST.
     7→  * assignments are now named SymASTxxx and the AST type includes both SymAST (identified with the AST type from 
     8→  * Assignmens 1-4). Some of the executable code in this interpreter mentions the types AST and 
     9→  * SDAST and related types to support anticipated code sharing in Project 7. The three types ASTVisitor, 
    10→  * SymASTVisitor, and SDASTVisitor are ugly.  We could eliminate SymASTVisitor and SDASTVisitor at the cost of less 
    11→  * precise static type checking (which has already been severely compromised by Java's weak support for generics).  
    12→  * This approach is a defensible (and perhaps simpler) design if you are using your own solutions to earlier 
    13→  * assignments as the starting point for Project 6 instead of this code base. */
    14→
    15→/** AST ::= SymAST | SDAST */
    16→interface AST {
    17→  /** This interface includes both SymASTs and SDASTs, which is unattractive from the perspective of type checking but
    18→    * it fosters code sharing.  Unfortunately, Java generics are restrictive so we cannot both (i) specify the data 
    19→    * domains that we really would like and (ii) aggressively share code.  To reduce the amount of code required for 
    20→    * Projects 6 and 7 we decided (ii) was a higher priority and compromised the quality of type checking. If Java
    21→    * had a richer type system, we could pass the intended AST subtype (either SymAST or SDAST) as a type parameter and 
    22→    * tailor shared code to achieve the appropriate behavior while accurately checking types but Java restricts the use of 
    23→    * type parameters, e.g., no arrays of type T[] or casts of the form (T) where T is a type parameter.  So we live 
    24→    * with the weaker type AST (instead of SymAST or SDAST) to share code and accept the weak static type checking 
    25→    * inherent in this design.  For typing purposes, an ASTVisitor supports both SymASTs and SDASTs. In practice, only 
    26→    * SymAST methods or SDAST methods are well-defined in a concrete ASTVisitor class; the others throw exceptions. We do not
    27→    * support ASTs that intermix SymAST and SDAST nodes. */
    28→  public <RtnType> RtnType accept(ASTVisitor<RtnType> v);
    29→}
    30→
    31→/** The AST type for conventional abstract syntax (with variables) */
    32→interface SymAST extends AST {
    33→  public <RtnType> RtnType accept(SymASTVisitor<RtnType> v);
    34→}
    35→
    36→/** The AST type for static distance coordinate abstract syntax */
    37→interface SDAST extends AST {
    38→  public <RtnType> RtnType accept(SDASTVisitor<RtnType> v);
    39→}
    40→
    41→/** The methods in SymASTVisitor + SDASTVisitor; none of our visitors actually works on both, but this approach assigns
    42→  * a common type to what are really SymASTVisitors and SDASTVisitors */
    43→interface ASTVisitor<RtnType> extends SymASTVisitor<RtnType>, SDASTVisitor<RtnType> {}
    44→
    45→/** The common methods in SymASTVisitor and SDASTVisitor.  This type is not used in Project 6. */
    46→interface ComASTVisitor<RtnType> {
    47→  RtnType forBoolConstant(BoolConstant b);
    48→  RtnType forIntConstant(IntConstant i);
    49→  RtnType forEmptyConstant(EmptyConstant n);
    50→  RtnType forPrimFun(PrimFun f);
    51→  RtnType forUnOpApp(UnOpApp u);
    52→  RtnType forBinOpApp(BinOpApp b);
    53→  RtnType forApp(App a);
    54→  RtnType forIf(If i); 
    55→  RtnType forBlock(Block i);
    56→}
    57→
    58→interface SymASTVisitor<RtnType> extends ComASTVisitor<RtnType> {
    59→  RtnType forVariable(Variable v);
    60→  RtnType forMap(Map m);
    61→  RtnType forLet(Let l);
    62→  RtnType forLetRec(LetRec l);
    63→  RtnType forLetcc(Letcc host);
    64→}
    65→
    66→interface SDASTVisitor<RtnType> extends ComASTVisitor<RtnType> {
    67→  RtnType forSDPair(SDPair p); 
    68→  RtnType forSMap(SMap sm);
    69→  RtnType forSLet(SLet sl);
    70→  RtnType forSLetRec(SLetRec slr);
    71→}
